{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499983"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:06:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1596"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1596"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.38,0.18,0.37,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1596"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1596"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78893"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"856"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48266"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of left lower quadrant pain that has since resolved. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no tenderness or masses. Routine blood tests and urinalysis are normal. A CT scan is performed as a precaution, which shows an incidental finding in the right upper quadrant (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for the incidental CT finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI scan","Reassurance","Yearly follow-up with ultrasound","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Open cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a porcelain gallbladder with selective areas of calcification. This is an incidental finding unrelated to the patient\u0027s recent episode of left lower quadrant pain, which may have been due to ureteric colic or diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient with a porcelain gallbladder showing selective mucosal calcification. While historically all porcelain gallbladders were thought to carry a high risk of malignancy, recent evidence suggests that the risk varies with the pattern of calcification. Selective mucosal calcification, as seen in this case, carries a higher risk of malignancy than complete intramural calcification. For an otherwise healthy patient without significant comorbidities, prophylactic removal is recommended to eliminate this risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inappropriate for this patient with selective mucosal calcification of the gallbladder. While the absolute risk of gallbladder cancer is still relatively low, it carries a poor prognosis when diagnosed late. Additionally, patients with porcelain gallbladders have an increased risk of developing symptomatic cholelithiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYearly follow-up with ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for patients with complete intramural calcification or those with significant comorbidities that increase surgical risk. However, for a healthy patient with selective mucosal calcification, surveillance alone is inadequate as it may miss early malignant transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI scan\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide significant additional information beyond what is already evident on the CT scan. The calcification pattern is already well-demonstrated, and further imaging would not change the management approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally recommended for porcelain gallbladder due to concerns that the calcified gallbladder would be too brittle for laparoscopic removal. However, current evidence supports laparoscopic cholecystectomy as the first-line approach, with conversion to open procedure only if technically necessary during the operation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Porcelain gallbladder with selective mucosal calcification carries a higher risk of malignancy than complete intramural calcification.","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the preferred management for porcelain gallbladder with selective mucosal calcification, even in asymptomatic patients.","Incidental findings on imaging require careful assessment of risk-benefit ratio before determining management."],"references":["Khan ZS, Livingston EH, Huerta S. Reassessing the Need for Prophylactic Surgery in Patients With Porcelain Gallbladder: Case Series and Systematic Review of the Literature. Arch Surg. 2011;146(10):1143\u20131147. doi:10.1001/archsurg.2011.257 Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22006872/","DesJardins H, Duy L, Scheirey C, Schnelldorfer T. Porcelain Gallbladder: Is Observation a Safe Option in Select Populations? J Am Coll Surg. 2018 Jun;226(6):1064-1069. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29505824/","Chen GL, Akmal Y, DiFronzo AL, et al. Porcelain Gallbladder: No Longer an Indication\nfor Prophylactic Cholecystectomy Am Surg 2018; 81:936-40. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26463284/","Morimoto M, Matsuo T, Mori N. Management of Porcelain Gallbladder, Its Risk Factors, and Complications: A Review. Diagnostics (Basel). 2021;11: 1073. doi:10.3390/diagnostics11061073. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34200963/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1596"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19907"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21073"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19907"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/358f56a7-1b71-4617-9af8-ba9a36b593a5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/358f56a7-1b71-4617-9af8-ba9a36b593a5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":328,"height":375}},{"type":"media","id":"21073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21073"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JLxhgH854B4FDGvkTg6Klo1bgivDNM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JLxhgH854B4FDGvkTg6Klo1bgivDNM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":328,"height":375}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T14:18:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T14:20:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1596"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https:/